{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a8fb105d-e517-432b-baf3-447565f9bd81","content":"Here's a step-by-step approach:\n\n**1. Get a shell into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` in the container:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a CPU trace (e.g., 30 seconds):**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**5. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**6. Analyze** in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n---\n\n**Alternative — if you can't install tools in the container:**\n\nSince you have **host admin access**, you can use `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar or use **PerfView** / **dotnet-counters** from the host. You can also add `dotnet-monitor` as a sidecar container in your pod spec to expose a diagnostics API without modifying the app container.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"55f7ddf0-dcbe-42e1-9a33-32a61ba95c86","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're seeing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/advisory question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, actionable guidance.","outputTokens":394,"requestId":"418E:36C261:638FBDD:6C95670:69F15DE0"},"id":"898cfa69-9a94-4faa-8516-62b7450bfeef","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:24:57.435Z","parentId":"9e460ff9-0a19-4f07-90bd-89a3cc31e72c"}
